Creating a meal plan using MATLAB involves organizing the components of each dish and processing them in a way that can be easily followed. While MATLAB isn't typically used for meal planning, we can use it to structure the ingredients and steps in a logical order. Below is a simplified representation of how you could approach this task using MATLAB:

```matlab
% Define the ingredients for each dish
zucchini_noodles = {'zucchini', 'avocado', 'basil', 'lemon juice', 'garlic', 'pine nuts', 'olive oil'};
watermelon_gazpacho = {'watermelon', 'cucumber', 'tomato', 'red bell pepper', 'red onion', 'lime juice', 'mint'};
cauliflower_sushi = {'cauliflower', 'nori sheets', 'carrot', 'cucumber', 'avocado', 'tamari'};
kale_chips = {'kale', 'olive oil', 'nutritional yeast', 'cayenne pepper', 'sea salt'};
coconut_yogurt_parfait = {'coconut yogurt', 'berries', 'granola', 'chia seeds', 'nuts'};

% Define a function to display a meal plan
function displayMealPlan
    fprintf('Five-Course Raw Food Meal Plan:\n');
    fprintf('1. Zucchini Noodles with Avocado Pesto\n');
    fprintf('   Ingredients: %s\n', strjoin(zucchini_noodles, ', '));
    fprintf('   Technique: Blending, Slicing\n\n');

    fprintf('2. Watermelon Gazpacho\n');
    fprintf('   Ingredients: %s\n', strjoin(watermelon_gazpacho, ', '));
    fprintf('   Technique: Blending, Dicing\n\n');

    fprintf('3. Cauliflower Rice Sushi Rolls\n');
    fprintf('   Ingredients: %s\n', strjoin(cauliflower_sushi, ', '));
    fprintf('   Technique: Slicing, Rolling\n\n');

    fprintf('4. Spicy Kale Chips\n');
    fprintf('   Ingredients: %s\n', strjoin(kale_chips, ', '));
    fprintf('   Technique: Massaging, Dehydrating\n\n');

    fprintf('5. Coconut Yogurt Parfait\n');
    fprintf('   Ingredients: %s\n', strjoin(coconut_yogurt_parfait, ', '));
    fprintf('   Technique: Layering\n');
end

% Call the function to display the meal plan
displayMealPlan;
```

This code outlines the ingredients for each dish and the techniques used. It doesn’t perform any calculations or optimizations, but it structures the information in a way that can be useful for planning. For a more advanced application, you might integrate nutritional data and use optimization techniques to balance nutrients, but that would require additional data and complexity beyond this basic overview.
